# Caravan Management

{{if eq .Role "envoy"}}A caravan logically groups a set of related writs into a unit of work that can be auto-dispatched by consul. The critical skill is not the commands — it is **getting the inter-writ DAG right** so work flows correctly and in parallel where possible.

## Mental Model

A caravan is a container for related writs. It exists so consul can auto-dispatch eligible items without you manually casting each one. The caravan itself has no inherent size constraints — it can hold 3 writs or 3000. What matters is that the ordering between writs is correct.

**Writ dependencies** are the primary ordering mechanism. They create a DAG: writ B waits for writ A to close (merge) before B becomes dispatchable. Everything without a dependency runs as soon as an agent is available.

**Phases** are a secondary grouping tool. All items in phase N must close before any item in phase N+1 becomes dispatchable. Phases exist for two situations:
- **Cross-world ordering**, where writ-level dependencies are not available (deps are world-scoped)
- **Sequential grouping**, where it is simpler to say "all of this before all of that" than to wire up point-to-point dependencies between many writs

## Dependencies vs Phases

**Writ dependencies** (`{{.Sol}} writ dep add <from> <to>`) are point-to-point. Writ B waits for writ A; everything else proceeds freely. This is the default tool for ordering. Use it whenever you can express the constraint as "this writ needs that writ's output."

**Phases** serialize everything across the boundary. They are a blunt instrument — appropriate when the work genuinely divides into "do all of this first, then all of that," or when cross-world constraints make writ-level deps impossible.

### Decision framework

- Specific writs need specific predecessors → **writ dependencies**
- Two writs touch the same files → **writ dependency** between them
- Work divides into broad sequential stages → **phases**
- Cross-world ordering needed → **phases** (deps are world-scoped)
- Writs are completely independent → **no deps, same phase**

## File Overlap

Before finalizing the DAG, think about which files each writ will modify:

- Two writs that touch the same file and run concurrently may collide at merge time. Add a writ dependency between them to serialize.
- Narrow writs (fewer files touched) have less collision risk than broad ones.

## Drydock vs Commissioned

A newly created caravan is in **drydock** — it exists but is not dispatchable. This is a deliberate staging area:

1. **Create** the caravan and add items
2. **Assign phases** and dependencies — get the DAG right
3. **Present** the structure to the operator for approval
4. **Commission** (`{{.Sol}} caravan commission <id>`) — marks it live and dispatchable. Consul begins auto-dispatching eligible items.

Commission triggers dispatch, so it is the step that requires operator approval. Everything before it (create, assign phases, set deps) is your call.

## Your Authority

You have full authority to create writs, structure caravans, assign phases, and set dependencies. You do **not** need operator approval for any of that. Get the DAG right and create the caravan.

**Dispatch requires explicit operator approval.** After assembling the caravan in drydock, present a high-level overview (what the caravan does, phase/dep structure, key risks) and wait for the operator to say go. Commissioning makes the caravan live and dispatchable, so treat it as the action that requires approval.

## Failure Modes

- **Phase won't advance:** Prior items must be "closed" (merged), not just "done." Check forge queue — items may be queued for merge.
- **`{{.Sol}} caravan launch` with no agents:** Exits with message. Wait for consul patrol or for agents to free up.
- **Merge conflict between phase items:** Two items in the same phase touched the same file. Add a writ dependency for next time. For now, resolve the conflict manually.

## Command Reference

| Command | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `{{.Sol}} caravan create "name" <id> [<id>...] --world={{.World}}` | Create caravan with items |
| `{{.Sol}} caravan add <caravan-id> <id> --world={{.World}}` | Add item to caravan |
| `{{.Sol}} caravan status [<caravan-id>]` | Check caravan progress |
| `{{.Sol}} caravan launch <caravan-id> --world={{.World}}` | Dispatch all ready items |
| `{{.Sol}} caravan commission <caravan-id>` | Mark caravan as commissioned (live) |
| `{{.Sol}} caravan set-phase <caravan-id> [<item-id>] <phase>` | Set phase for one item (integer: 0, 1, 2 — not p0/p1/p2) |
| `{{.Sol}} caravan set-phase <caravan-id> --all <phase>` | Set phase for all items (integer: 0, 1, 2) |
| `{{.Sol}} caravan check <caravan-id>` | Check phase-gate readiness |
| `{{.Sol}} caravan list` | List all caravans |
| `{{.Sol}} caravan dep add <caravan-id> <dep-id>` | Add inter-caravan dependency |
| `{{.Sol}} caravan dep list <caravan-id>` | List caravan dependencies |

**Writ-level dependencies** (used within caravans for point-to-point ordering):

| Command | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `{{.Sol}} writ dep add <from> <to>` | Writ `<from>` waits for `<to>` to close |
| `{{.Sol}} writ dep list <id>` | List dependencies for a writ |

**Setup flow:** create writs → `{{.Sol}} caravan create` → assign phases → set dependencies → present to operator → `{{.Sol}} caravan commission` (with approval).{{else}}Commands for grouping and sequencing related writs.

